1. Monolithic Vs Microservices

The main difference is that a monolithic architecture builds an application as one single unit, while a microservices architecture breaks 
it into a collection of smaller, independent services

Quick Comparison

Monolithic Architecture                                    Microservices Architecture
One large codebase                                         Many small codebases
Simple to start                                            Complex to design
Single point of failure                                    Isolated failures
Shared database                                            Separate databases
Scales all at once                                         Scales pieces separately

Monolithic Architecture.

Easy Setup: It is very simple to build, test, and deploy at first.
Fast Changes: You can change parts easily because everything is in one place.
Big Risk: If one small piece breaks, the whole application can crash.
Hard Scaling: To grow the app, you must copy the whole giant system onto new servers.

Microservices Architecture

Smart Growth: You can scale up just the busy parts without touching the rest.
Safe Coding: If one block breaks, the other parts keep working fine.
Tech Freedom: Teams can use different computer languages for different blocks.
High Complexity: It is hard to connect, secure, and test all the moving pieces.

2. Kubernetes architecture

Kubernetes architecture works like a shipping port that manages container ships, where a central control tower coordinates workers to load,
move, and monitor cargo. It uses a Control Plane to make decisions and Worker Nodes to run your applications.

The Control Plane (The Brain)
The Control Plane makes choices about your cluster. It detects when things break and starts up new apps.

API Server: The front door for all commands.
etcd: The secure backing store that holds all cluster data.
Scheduler: The guide that chooses which node runs a new app.
Controller Manager: The boss that keeps the actual state matching your desired state.
Cloud Controller: The bridge that talks to cloud providers like Google Cloud or AWS.

Worker Nodes (The Muscle)
Worker Nodes do the actual heavy lifting. They host the containers that form your application.

Kubelet: The captain on the ship that ensures containers run safely.
Kube-Proxy: The network helper that lets traffic reach your apps.
Container Runtime: The software, like Docker or containerd, that runs the containers.
Pods: The smallest building blocks that hold one or more containers.

How They Talk

You tell the API Server what you want using a tool like kubectl. The Scheduler finds a Worker Node with free space. The Kubelet on that
node takes over and starts the Pod.

Kubernetes cluster
A Kubernetes cluster is a set of node machines that run containerised applications together as a single system. It acts like a team of 
computers working under one manager to make sure your apps stay online, scale up smoothly, and never drop traffic.

The Two Main Parts
A cluster always needs two types of machines to function:

The Control Plane: The manager computer that coordinates everything.
Worker Nodes: The worker computers that run your apps inside Pods.

Essential Cluster Features
Self-Healing: If a container crashes, the cluster restarts it right away.
Auto-Scaling: It adds more nodes or pods automatically when traffic spikes.
Load Balancing: It distributes web traffic evenly so no single machine gets overloaded.
High Availability: If one computer breaks, your app keeps running on the other ones.

Ways to Get a Cluster

Type                Best For                  Popular Options
Managed Cloud      Real business apps         Google GKE, AWS EKS, Azure AKS
Local / Learning   Testing on your laptop     Minikube, Kind, K3s
Bare Metal         Full control of hardware   Kubeadm setup on your own servers

A Kubernetes cluster turns multiple separate computers into one massive supercomputer for running apps. 
It automates the hard work of managing software so humans do not have to watch it 24/7.

